<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,872,1368]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1089,1115]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">Distribution</emphasis>
. Cosmopolitan in warm seas. In the eastern Pacific distributed off the Columbia River, 
<collectingCountry box="[1373,1432,1089,1115]" name="United States of America" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">USA</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingRegion box="[245,419,1125,1151]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">Baja California</collectingRegion>
, and to the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[635,751,1125,1151]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">California</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[763,849,1125,1151]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E." box="[863,1161,1125,1152]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" pagination="139 - 154" refId="ref14339" refString="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E. (2005) Cap. 12. Crustacea 4. Lophogastrida, Mysida, Amphipoda, Tanaidacea &amp; Cumacea. In: Hendrickx, M. E., Brusca, R. C. &amp; Findley L. T. (Eds.), A Distributional Checklist of the Macrofauna of the Gulf of California, Mexico. Part I. Invertebrates. [Listado y Distribucion de la Macrofauna del Golfo de California, Mexico, Parte I. Invertebrados]. Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum, Tucson, Arizona, pp. 139 - 154." type="book chapter" year="2005">Brusca &amp; Hendrickx 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia Madrigal, M. S." box="[1173,1425,1125,1151]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" pagination="63 - 195" refId="ref14782" refString="Garcia Madrigal, M. S. (2007) Annotated checklist of the amphipods (Peracarida: Amphipoda) from the tropical eastern Pacific. Contributions to the Study of East Pacific Crustaceans, 4 (2), 63 - 195." type="journal article" year="2007">García Madrigal 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Our observations allow an extension of its southernmost distribution limit in the eastern Pacific to SW 
<collectingCountry box="[1351,1437,1161,1187]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[160,301,1197,1224]" degrees="17" direction="north" minutes="27" orientation="latitude" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" precision="15" seconds="51" value="17.464167">17°27’51”N</geoCoordinate>
). Present in surface waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." box="[615,878,1197,1224]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" refId="ref16750" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis box="[756,805,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">et al</emphasis>
. 1996
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="171" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,872,1368]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1233,1259]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Siegel-Causey, D." box="[323,568,1233,1259]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" refId="ref16354" refString="Siegel-Causey, D. (1982) Factors determining the distribution of hyperiid Amphipoda in the Gulf of California. Ph. D. Thesis, University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizona, 535 pp." type="book" year="1982">Siegel-Causey (1982)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species in the southern Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[1085,1199,1233,1259]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="2" pageNumber="171">California</collectingRegion>
in three seasons and classified it as an “uncommon” species in the area but noted its presence throughout the Gulf in earlier samplings. A surface water species, recorded in the 
<quantity box="[601,686,1305,1331]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="6.6" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" unit="m" value="33.0" valueMax="66.0" valueMin="0.0">0‒66 m</quantity>
depth layer (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia Madrigal, M. S." box="[831,1084,1305,1331]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" pagination="63 - 195" refId="ref14782" refString="Garcia Madrigal, M. S. (2007) Annotated checklist of the amphipods (Peracarida: Amphipoda) from the tropical eastern Pacific. Contributions to the Study of East Pacific Crustaceans, 4 (2), 63 - 195." type="journal article" year="2007">García Madrigal 2007</bibRefCitation>
), but also mentioned as a “middepth” species by 
<bibRefCitation author="Siegel-Causey, D." box="[356,601,1341,1367]" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" refId="ref16354" refString="Siegel-Causey, D. (1982) Factors determining the distribution of hyperiid Amphipoda in the Gulf of California. Ph. D. Thesis, University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizona, 535 pp." type="book" year="1982">Siegel-Causey (1982)</bibRefCitation>
, roughly in the 
<quantity box="[777,904,1341,1368]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="171" unit="m" value="300.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="100.0">100‒500 m</quantity>
depth range.
</paragraph>
